5|$|Relations between Nasser and Qasim grew {{increasingly}} bitter on 9 March, after Qasim's forces suppressed a rebellion <b>in</b> <b>Mosul,</b> launched {{a day earlier}} by a pro-Nasser Iraqi RCC officer backed by UAR authorities. Nasser had considered dispatching troops to aid his Iraqi sympathizers, but decided against it. He clamped down on Egyptian communist activity due to the key backing Iraqi communists provided Qasim. Several influential communists were arrested, including Nasser's old comrade Khaled Mohieddin, who {{had been allowed to}} re-enter Egypt in 1956.|$|E
